PSR Draft: Result + Diagnostics Side Channel

Below is a full “PSR-style” spec text and a complete reference implementation (kernel + optional sink). Adjust names (PSR-XX) later.

SPEC.md (Normative)
Abstract

This specification defines a Result return type for operations that may succeed or fail, and a Diagnostics side channel that allows operations to attach structured, machine-readable events (diagnostics) to either outcome. Diagnostics are data, designed for deterministic composition and optional emission to sinks (e.g., loggers).

Motivation

PHP commonly relies on exceptions and global logging. Many operations, however, produce non-fatal signals (warnings, notices, recoverable issues, telemetry) that callers may want to observe without using exceptions or hidden global side effects.

This specification provides:

A Result type for explicit success/failure.

A Diagnostics channel carried alongside the result.

A sink mechanism to emit diagnostics at boundaries without forcing global mutable state.

Scope

This specification defines:

Level (severity)

Diagnostic (structured event)

Diagnostics (ordered collection)

Result (success/failure + diagnostics)

DiagnosticSink (optional sink for emission)

Non-goals

This specification does not define:

message formatting, localization, or templating

mapping to PSR-3 log levels (may be provided as an adapter)

exception policies (exceptions remain valid for exceptional conditions)

persistence/storage/transport formats for diagnostics

Terminology

Diagnostic: a structured, machine-readable event produced during an operation.

Diagnostics: an ordered collection of Diagnostic.

Result: a wrapper representing either success or failure, plus Diagnostics.

Sink: an endpoint that consumes diagnostics (e.g., logger, telemetry system).

Interfaces and Types
Level

Level is an enum providing an ordered severity scale.

Higher Level means “more severe”.

Diagnostic

A Diagnostic MUST provide:

id(): string — stable identifier treated as public API

level(): Level — severity for filtering and ordering policies

context(): array — structured payload

Diagnostics

Diagnostics is an ordered collection of Diagnostic.

Order MUST be preserved.

Composition MUST be deterministic.

Result

A Result contains:

either a success value, or an error value (domain-defined)

always a Diagnostics instance

DiagnosticSink

A sink consumes diagnostics.

Normative Semantics
Diagnostic identifiers

Diagnostic::id() MUST be stable API. Renaming an id is a backwards-incompatible change.

Ids MUST be unique within a producer/package namespace.

Context contract

Diagnostic::context() MUST return an associative array at the root with string keys.

Context values MUST be recursively representable using:

null, bool, int, float, string

objects implementing Stringable

arrays of the same

Context MUST NOT contain resources or closures.

Nested arrays MAY be:

maps (string keys)

lists (0..n-1) (SHOULD use consecutive keys from 0)

Diagnostics ordering

Diagnostics MUST preserve insertion order.

When composing results, diagnostics MUST be concatenated left-to-right in evaluation order.

Result composition

Result::map() MUST preserve diagnostics unchanged.

Result::andThen() MUST:

if the receiver is failure: return failure without invoking callback; diagnostics unchanged

if success: invoke callback; return its result; diagnostics MUST be concatenated left-to-right

Sink emission guidance (non-normative but recommended)

Diagnostics are returned by default (local/data channel).

Emission to sinks SHOULD happen at application boundaries (controllers, commands, job handlers).

If diagnostics are emitted internally for streaming telemetry, such emitted items SHOULD NOT also be returned (to avoid duplication). (Rule Option 1)

